  <content>
    <para id="para-00001">If you imagine removing a hydrogen atom from an alkane, the partial structure that remains is called an <term id="term-00001"><emphasis effect="bold">alkyl group</emphasis></term>. Alkyl groups are not stable compounds themselves, they are simply parts of larger compounds and are named by replacing the -<emphasis effect="italics">ane</emphasis> ending of the parent alkane with an -<emphasis effect="italics">yl</emphasis> ending. For example, removal of a hydrogen from methane, CH<sub>4</sub>, generates a methyl group, &#8201;–&#8201;CH<sub>3</sub>, and removal of a hydrogen from ethane, CH<sub>3</sub>CH<sub>3</sub>, generates an ethyl group, &#8201;–&#8201;CH<sub>2</sub>CH<sub>3</sub>. Similarly, removal of a hydrogen atom from the end carbon of any straight-chain alkane gives the series of straight-chain alkyl groups shown in <link target-id="table-00001"/>. Combining an alkyl group with any of the functional groups listed earlier makes it possible to generate and name many thousands of compounds. For example:</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00001">
    <media alt="An illustration shows four molecular structures and their corresponding ball-and-stick models. The first structure “methane” shows a centrally located carbon bonded to four hydrogen atoms; the ball-and-stick model shows a centrally located carbon bonded to four hydrogens; the grey balls denote carbon atoms and white balls denote hydrogen atoms. The second structure “a methyl group” shows a centrally located carbon bonded to three hydrogen atoms and a fourth open bond intersected by a short pink spiral line; the ball-and-stick model shows carbon bonded to three hydrogens and the fourth bond being cut off by a short pink spiral line. The third structure “methyl alcohol (methanol)” shows a centrally located carbon bonded to three hydrogen atoms on three sides and an oxygen written in pink color shown to its right the oxygen is bonded to hydrogen; the ball-and-stick model shows a carbon bonded to three hydrogens and to its right is shown a red ball representing an oxygen bonded to a hydrogen. The fourth structure “methylamine” shows a carbon bonded to three hydrogen atoms the carbon is further bonded to a nitrogen written in blue color having a downward and a side bond with hydrogen; the ball and stick model shows a carbon bonded to three hydrogens the carbon is bonded to a blue ball representing nitrogen that is bonded to two hydrogens.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_03_03_001.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
