    <para id="para-00002">Just as straight-chain alkyl groups are generated by removing a hydrogen from an end carbon, branched alkyl groups are generated by removing a hydrogen atom from an internal carbon. Two 3-carbon alkyl groups and four 4-carbon alkyl groups are possible (<link target-id="fig-00002"/>).</para>
    <figure class="scaled-down" id="fig-00002">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two sections comprising of nine alkyl groups along with their structures and ball-and-stick models wherein the grey balls denote carbon and white balls denote hydrogen. The first section C3 shows propane propyl and isopropyl. The structure of propane shows a methyl group bonded to methylene group bonded to a methyl group. The structure of propyl shows a methyl group bonded to two consecutive methylene groups the open bond attached to methylene group shows a split in the form of a short pink spiral line. The structure of an isopropyl shows a centrally located methine having an upward bond that is intersected with a pink short line; the methine is surrounded by two methyl groups on its sides. The second section C4 shows six alkyl groups. The first group is butane shown as a methyl bonded to two consecutive methylene groups attached to a methyl group. The second structure is a butyl shown as a methyl bonded to three consecutive methylene groups; the third methylene shows an open bond intersected by a pink spiral line. The third structure is sec-Butyl having a methyl group bonded to a methylene group attached to a methine having an upward open bond intersected by a pink spiral line the methine is further bonded to a methyl group. The fourth structure isobutane shows a methyl group bonded to a methine group having an upward and side bonds with methyl groups. The fifth structure “Isobutyl” shows a centrally located methine group bonded to methyl groups in an upward and side bond; the methine is further bonded to a methylene group having an open bond intersected by a pink spiral line. The sixth structure “tert-Butyl shows a centrally located carbon having an open bond intersected by a pink spiral line and shows three bonds with methyl groups on its three sides. The ball-and-stick models represent the structures with grey balls (carbons) and white balls (hydrogens).">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_03_03_002.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption>Alkyl groups generated from straight-chain alkanes.</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00003">One further comment about naming alkyl groups: the prefixes <emphasis effect="italics">sec</emphasis>- (for secondary) and <emphasis effect="italics">tert</emphasis>- (for tertiary) used for the C<sub>4</sub> alkyl groups in <link target-id="fig-00003"/> refer to the number of other carbon atoms attached to the branching carbon atom. There are four possibilities: primary (1°), secondary (2°), tertiary (3°), and quaternary (4°).</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
    <media alt="An illustration shows four ways of naming alkyl groups. The carbons shown in the groups are colored pink and the R are colored blue. The first group labeled as “Primary carbon (1 degree) is bonded to one other carbon” shows a centrally located carbon bonded to R on the upper left side and three hydrogen atoms are shown bonded on three sides. The second group labeled as “Secondary carbon (two degree) is bonded to three other carbons” shows a centrally located carbon bonded to two R and two hydrogen atoms. The third group labeled as “Tertiary carbon (three degree) is bonded to three other carbons” shows a centrally located carbon bonded to three R and one hydrogen atom. The fourth group “Quaternary carbon (four degree) is bonded to four other carbons” shows a centrally located carbon bonded to four R.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_03_03_003.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00004">The symbol <emphasis effect="bold">R</emphasis> is used here and throughout organic chemistry to represent a generalized organic group. The <term id="term-00002"><emphasis effect="bold">R group</emphasis></term> can be methyl, ethyl, propyl, or any of a multitude of others. You might think of <emphasis effect="bold">R</emphasis> as representing the <emphasis effect="bold">R</emphasis>est of the molecule, which isn’t specified.</para>
    <para id="para-00005">The terms <emphasis effect="italics">primary, secondary, tertiary,</emphasis> and <emphasis effect="italics">quaternary</emphasis> are routinely used in organic chemistry, and their meanings need to become second nature. For example, if we were to say, “Citric acid is a tertiary alcohol,” we would mean that it has an alcohol functional group (&#8201;–&#8201;OH) bonded to a carbon atom that is itself bonded to three other carbons.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down-30" id="fig-00004">
    <media alt="An illustration shows two structures. The first structure labeled as “General class of tertiary alcohols R3COH” shows a centrally located carbon having an upward bond with a hydroxyl group written in pink and three bonds with R written in blue. The second structure labeled as “Citric acid - a specific tertiary alcohol” shows a centrally located carbon having an upward bond with a hydroxyl group written in pink; the three groups bonded on other three sides are shown in blue; a group comprising of a methylene group bonded to a carbon dioxide bonded to hydrogen are shown on both left and right sides of carbon; the carbon shows a downward bond with bicarbonate HCO2.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_03_03_004.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00006">In addition to speaking of carbon atoms as being primary, secondary, or tertiary, we speak of hydrogens in the same way. Primary hydrogen atoms are attached to primary carbons (RCH<sub>3</sub>), secondary hydrogens are attached to secondary carbons (R<sub>2</sub>CH<sub>2</sub>), and tertiary hydrogens are attached to tertiary carbons (R<sub>3</sub>CH). There is, however, no such thing as a quaternary hydrogen. (Why not?)</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
    <media alt="An illustration shows three types of hydrogens in a compound; also shown is an expansion of the molecular structure of the compound. The structure shows a methyl group bonded to a methylene group bonded to a methine group; the methine group shows an upward and a side bond with methyl groups. The hydrogens of the methyl groups are shown in pink and text read “Primary hydrogens (CH3); the hydrogen of methylene groups are in blue and the text reads “Secondary hydrogens (CH2)”; the hydrogen of methine group is in green and the text reads “A tertiary hydrogen (CH).” This structure is shown expanded in a parenthesis wherein four consecutive carbons are shown as a chain; the first carbon is bonded to three hydrogens shown as pink; the second carbon is bonded to two hydrogens shown as blue; the third carbon shows an upward bond with another carbon bonded to three hydrogens shown as pink; the third carbon also shows a downward bond with hydrogen shown as green; the fourth carbon is bonded to three hydrogens shown as pink.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_03_03_005.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
